text: Organic & Biomolecular Chemistry Cite this: DOI: 10.1039/d1ob00310k Received 19th February 2021, Accepted 5th April 2021 Benzoﬂuorene-containing atypical angucyclines are an important family of natural products with a broad spectrum of antibacterial and cytotoxic properties. Interestingly, symmetric and asymmetric dimers showed better activity than the monomer in this class of compounds. Herein, we reported the isolation of a new asymmetric from the deep sea actinomycete dimer nenestatin B (2) Micromonospora echinospora SCSIO 04089 and a monomer nenestatin C (3) from an NmrA family regulatory protein coding gene nes18 inactivated mutant. The structural elucidation of 3 indicated the essential role of Nes18 in the biosynthetic pathway of 2, speciﬁcally in dimerization via C–C bond formation. Benzofluorene-containing atypical angucyclines, an important family of natural products, are usually biosynthesized by type II polyketide synthases (PKSs).1–3 The type II PKS-derived pre- cursors can undergo unusual tailoring modifications, such as oxidative rearrangements, leading to structurally diverse atypi- cal angucyclines.1,4 Representative examples include kinamy- cins,5 lomaiviticins,6–8 nenestatin (NEN) A (1),9 and fluostatins (Fig. 1).10,11 This family of atypical angucyclines displays a broad spectrum of potent and cytotoxic activities.1,4 For example, lomaiviticin A exhibits cytotoxicity of nanomolar to picomolar concentrations toward a panel of human cancer cell lines by inducing double-strand breaks in DNA, and is currently under preclinical evaluation for antitu- mor treatment.12–14 It is noteworthy that the symmetric dimer

lomaiviticin A shows hundred-fold better activity than the monomer kinamycin C.13,14 Interestingly, the C1–C5′ asym- metric heterodimer difluostatin A also exhibits stronger anti- bacterial activity than its respective monomer.11 It seems that dimerization is important to amplify the therapeutic potential of this class of compounds.15 An early hypothesis speculated that the production of C–C dimers, including actinorhodins, lomaiviticin A and difluostatin A, might be catalyzed by the NmrA family regulatory proteins ActVA-ORF4,16,17 Lom19,18 and FlsQ1,11 respectively. Our recent study demonstrated that the formation of fluostatin dimers was a nonenzymatic process via a spontaneous C–C or C–N coupling mediated by a reactive para-quinone methide species, and the enzyme FlsQ1 was confirmed to be unrelated to dimer formation.19 However, Fig. 1 Chemical structures of representative benzoﬂuorene-containing atypical angucyclines. a,b,c Chunfang Yang,a,c Haibo Zhang, given that the role of ActVA-ORF4 in forming actinorhodin dimers was validated,16 one could not exclude the involvement of Lom19 in catalyzing the C–C coupling reaction in lomaiviti- cin A.18

NEN A (1) was reported from the deep sea actinomycete Micromonospora echinospora SCSIO 04089.9 Recently, upon the assistance of resin absorption, more structurally diverse angu- cycline derivatives were isolated from M. echinospora SCSIO 04089, putatively as biosynthetic intermediates or shunt pro- ducts in the NEN A (1) biosynthetic pathway.20 The monomeric core structure of lomaiviticin A was recently revised to be similar to the benzo[b]fluorene carbon scaﬀold of 1 (Fig. 1).8 The biosynthetic gene cluster (BGC) of 1 (nes) also shares almost identical organization with the lomaiviticin BGCs (lom) from Salinispora tropica CNB-44021 and S. pacifica DPJ-0016 and DPJ-0019.18 Interestingly, comparative bioinformatics ana- lysis revealed the presence of an NmrA family regulatory protein Nes18 encoded in the nes BGC. However, its role in 1 biosynthesis remained unclear. Herein, we reported the iso- lation of a new asymmetric dimer NEN B (2) from M. echinospora SCSIO 04089 and a new monomer NEN C (3) from the nes18-inactivated mutant (Δnes18). The structural elucidation of NEN B (2) was assisted by its deglycosylated derivative NEN D (4) via acid hydrolysis. In contrast to a sym- metric C-2–C-2′ coupling in lomaiviticin A, an asymmetric C-2– C-1′ linkage was found in NEN B (2) (Fig. 2). Our study implied that the NmrA family regulatory protein Nes18 might be responsible for the C-2–C-1′ dimerization of NEN B (2).

We previously reported the isolation and characterization of NEN A (1) from M. echinospora SCSIO 04089 in N4 media, and the detection of 2 (Fig. 2) as an uncharacterized main product.9 We then performed a 20 L fermentation of M. echinospora SCSIO 04089 in N4 media and isolated 2 as a pure compound. The molecular formula of 2 was determined as C56H62N2O17 (m/z 1033.3977 [M − H] , calcd for 1033.3975, Fig. 2 The mutagenesis strategy and fermentation proﬁles of the Δnes18 mutant and structures of the isolated compounds. The Δnes18 mutant was constructed by insertional mutagenesis, and comparative HPLC analysis of the metabolite proﬁles was carried out for (i) the wild type (WT) strain M. echinospora SCSIO 04089; (ii) the Δnes18 mutant; and (iii) the acid hydrolysis product of 2. Structures of 2–4 are also shown.

Fig. S1†) by high-resolution electrospray ionization mass spec- trometry (HRESIMS). The NMR signals of 2 were found to be seriously overlapped and not well split in a variety of deute- rated solvents and DMSO-d6) (Fig. S1†). Detailed analysis of the NMR spectra of 2 in DMSO- d6 showed the presence of four exchange protons, six sp2 meth- ines, two methoxy, seven oxidative methines (including two hemiacetal methines), two doublet methyls, and two triplet methyls, together with indefinite methylenes and nonproto- nated carbons (Fig. S1†). A careful comparison of the NMR data of 2 and 1 revealed the presence of two sugar units of 4-O- methyl-L-angolosamine in 2 (Table S1†), the same as that in 1.9 The assignment of the sugar units was confirmed by COSY cor- relations S), H-3S(3′S)/H-4S(4′S), H-4S(4′S)/H-5S(5′S) and H-5S(5′S)/H3-6S(6′S) and HMBC correlations from H3-6S(6′S) to C-5S(5′S)/C-4S(4′S) and from H3-7S(7′ S) (Fig. 3, Fig. S1, Table S1†). These data preliminarily indicated that 2 might be a dimeric compound with each monomer containing a 4-O-methyl-L- angolosamine. However, its structure was unable to be deter- mined by NMR due to serious signal overlaps.

Subsequently, we performed a comparative bioinformatics analysis and revealed that an NmrA family regulatory protein Nes18 was encoded in the nes BGC of M. echinospora SCSIO 04089,9 homologous to the putative dimerases Lom19 (83.6%)18 and ActVA-ORF4 (47.3%).16 We then attempted to inactivate nes18 to see if we could get monomeric products to facilitate the structure elucidation of 2. To this end, the nes18 gene was disrupted in M. echinospora SCSIO 04089 to aﬀord the Δnes18 mutant (NES004) (Fig. S2, Tables S2 and S3†). A subsequent HPLC analysis revealed that the production of 2 was abolished in the Δnes18 mutant; instead, a distinct Fig. 3 Selected key COSY, HMBC and NOESY correlations of 3 and 4, and comparison of the experimental and calculated ECD spectra of 3. product was observed (Fig. 2). A scaled-up fermentation of the Δnes18 mutant led to the isolation of 3. Compound 3 was iso- lated as a red amorphous powder. The molecular formula of 3 was determined as C19H14O6 (m/z 337.0719 [M − H] , calcd for 337.0717, Fig. S3†) by HRESIMS. Analysis of the 1H, 13C and heteronuclear single quantum coherence (HSQC) NMR data of 3 revealed the presence of signals for three exchangeable protons, two keto carbonyl groups, nine sp2 nonprotonated carbons, five sp2 methines, an oxidative sp3 nonprotonated carbon, a methylene and a methyl (Table 1, Fig. S3†). The NMR data of 3 were highly similar to those of NEN A (1). The only diﬀerence was that the NMR signals for the 4-O-methyl-L- angolosamine sugar moiety in 1 were absent in 3.9 Instead, an exchangeable proton signal (δ H 4.98) was found, which was attributed to 3-OH by HMBC correlations from 3-OH to C-2/ C-3/C-4/C-12 (Fig. 3, Fig. S3†). Thus, 3 was structurally eluci- dated to be the deglycosylated aglycon of 1 (Fig. 2). The absol- ute configuration of C-3 in 3 was verified by the comparison of the experimental ECD curve with the calculated ECD curves of two enantiomers (3R)-3 and (3S)-3. The experimental ECD spectrum of 3 was in agreement with the calculated ECD spec- trum of (3S)-3, confirming the absolute configuration of 3 as 3S (Fig. 3). Thus, the structure of 3 was established and designed as NEN C (Fig. 2). product 4. The molecular formula of 4 was established as C38H28O13 by HRESIMS (m/z 691.1458 [M − H] , calcd for 691.1457, Fig. S4†). Compound 4 diﬀered from 2 by the loss of C18H34N2O4, equal to two molecules of 4-O-methyl-L- angolosa- mine, consistent with the fact that 4 was a deglycosylated product of 2.9 Interpretation of the NMR data of 4 (Table 1, Fig. S4†) showed the presence of two units A and B, both of which were structurally similar to 3.9 Unit A diﬀered from 3 at C-1 and C-2. A double bond Δ1,2 was present in 3 (Fig. 2, Table 1). In contrast, a single C-1–C-2 bond was assigned in unit A by connecting a methylene (δ H 25.8/3.31, 2.77, CH2- 1) and a methine (δC/δH 47.2/3.22, CH-2). The assignment was confirmed by the COSY correlation between H2-1/H-2 and HMBC correlations from H2-1 to C-2/C-11a/C-11b, from H-2 to C-1/C-4/C-11b/C-12 and from H2-12 to C-2 (Fig. 3, Fig. S4†). Diﬀerent from two sp2 methines (δC/δH 126.8/7.52, C-1; δC/δH 132.5/5.80, C-2) in 3, unit B was found to have an sp2 nonpro- tonated carbon (δC/δH 141.3, C-1′) and an oxidative sp3 methine (δC/δH 61.7/3.79, C-2′). The location of the methine at C-2′ was supported by HMBC correlations from H-2′ to C-3′/ C-4′/C-12′ and from H2-12′

δC/δH 61.7/3.79, C-2′). The location of the methine at C-2′ was supported by HMBC correlations from H-2′ to C-3′/ C-4′/C-12′ and from H2-12′ to C-2′ (Fig. 3, Fig. S4†). In addition, HMBC correlations from H2-1 and H-2 to C-1′ were observed in 4 (Fig. 3, Fig. S4†), supporting that the two units A and B were connected through the C2–C1′ bond. Thus, 4 was elucidated as a C2–C1′ asymmetric heterodimer (Fig. 2). The relative con- figuration of H-2 and H2-12 was assigned cis by NOESY corre- lations between H-2 and H2-12/H3-13. The cis-configuration of H-2′ and H2-12′ was deduced from NOESY correlations between H-2′ and H2-12′. Taken together with the NOESY cor- relation of H-2 and H-2′, only two possible absolute configur- ations could be assigned to 4, namely, 2R,3S,2′S,3′S or 2S,3R,

2′R,3′R (Fig. 3, Fig. S4†). From a biosynthetic point of view, the absolute configuration of C-3 and C-3′ in 4 should be 3S and 3′ S, the same as that in monomer 3. These assignments were strongly supported by close chemical shift values of C3/C3′ in 4 and of C-3 in 3. Therefore, the absolute configuration of 4 was tentatively assigned 2R,3S,2′S,3′S (Fig. 2). Since 4 was derived from 2 by sugar hydrolysis, we assumed that 4 should be the aglycon of 2. In addition, HMBC correlations from H-1S (or H-1′S) of 4-O-methyl-L-angolosamine to C-3 (or C-3′) in 2 (Fig. S1†) indicated that a 4-O-methyl-L-angolosamine sugar should be attached at both C-3 and C-3′, respectively. Finally, the structure of 2 was disclosed as shown in Fig. 2. The cytotoxicities of 1–4 were assayed against SF-268, MCF-7, A549, and HepG2 cell lines by the SRB method.22 Unfortunately, none showed cytotoxic activities towards these indicator cell lines. Compounds 1–4 showed no antibacterial activities against Escherichia coli ATCC 25922, Staphylococcus aureus ATCC 29213, Micrococcus SCSIO ML01, faecalis ATCC29212, Acinetobacter baumannii Enterococcus ATCC 19606, methicillin-resistant S. aureus ATCC 43300 and Vibrio alginolyticus XSBZ14 (a coral pathogenic bacterium23).

The accumulation of the monomer NEN C (3) and the con- comitant abolished production of the dimer NEN B (2) in the Δnes18 mutant indicated that the NmrA family regulatory protein Nes18 should play an important role in mediating a C– C bond-forming reaction to produce NEN B (2), probably from NEN C (3), similar to its homologous proteins ActVA-ORF4 and Lom19 and lomaiviticins.16,18 It has been reported that the NmrA family regulatory protein includes a structural superfamily of short- chain dehydrogenase/reductases.24 Recently, two NmrA-like SDR KstA10 and KstA11 were shown to catalyze a reduction– dearomatization process and a reduction–dehydration process in the kosinostatin biosynthetic pathway.25 As such, we hypoth- esized a C–C dimerization mechanism to form 2 from 3 (Scheme 1). Putatively, deprotonation of 11-OH in NEN C (3) leads to a phenolate anion, which undergoes resonance to yield the nucleophilic carbanion intermediate 3a. Next, 3a reacts with O2, most likely catalyzed by Nes18, to form the highly reactive hydroperoxide intermediate 3b. Then, 3b undergoes a protonation and an elimination of water to give 3c, a quinone methide species, a process that resembles KstA15 catalysis.24 Subsequently, a spontaneous nucleophilic addition between 3a and 3c leads to C-2–C-1′ coupling to build the asymmetric heterodimer 4a. This process is highly similar to the formation of difluostatin A.19 A following reduction of 4a yields NEN D (4). Finally, two 4-O-methyl-L-angolosamine units are respectively attached to C-3 and C-3′ OH of 4 to produce NEN B (2).9 Unfortunately, in an attempt to find out whether compound 3 was a true precursor of NEN B (2) by feeding experiments, we found that 3 failed to enter the cell of the

C-3 and C-3′ OH of 4 to produce NEN B (2).9 Unfortunately, in an attempt to find out whether compound 3 was a true precursor of NEN B (2) by feeding experiments, we found that 3 failed to enter the cell of the Δnes53 (encoding a beta unit of ketosynthase9) mutant of M. echinospora SCSIO 04089, which abolished the production of NENs (Fig. S5†). A similar 1,6-addition reaction was pro- posed for the biosynthetic oxidative coupling of monomeric diazofluorenes to construct the lomaiviticin A aglycon via a

C-2–C-2′ symmetric linkage.26 We supposed that the conver- sion of 3 to 4 was most likely catalyzed by the enzyme Nes18 to form a C-2–C-1′ asymmetric coupling. However, the proposed mechanism is still awaited for in vitro functional characteriz- ation of Nes18. In conclusion, a new asymmetric dimer NEN B (2) was isolated and characterized from M. echinospora SCSIO 04089, and in vivo genetic experiments showed that inactivation of the NmrA family regulatory protein-encoding gene nes18 led to the production of a monomeric product NEN C (3). This study pro- vided strong evidence to support an essential role of Nes18 in catalyzing an oxidative reaction to initiate a spontaneous C–C bond formation to yield dimer 2. X. Jiang, Z.
